replies.body:
With all due respect, a good duo top lane performs just as well as a good duo bot lane. Levels are powerful, yes, but a 2v1 is still a 2v1. Also, with the supports lately and how ADCs work, you can simply ward and escape easily with a ADC like Tristana, a tank like Braum, or Thresh lantern. You are looking at this on paper when I doubt you have ever made an actual team composition out of it. You say the jungler will go to the enemy jungle and farm on their blues and reds and various monsters, but that can all be countered by simply warding and your duo lanes can pick them up at the start of the game each for a huge early game advantage. Or Middle Lane can take it. Suddenly, bottom/top lane walks into lane with a Level 1 Red Buff, Middle Lane walks into lane with blue buff. Suddenly the lanes have a huge advantage and, with the Season 5 changes to Red Buff, you can push down towers much quicker early game due to the bonus true damage.

Early Game
Lanes walk out. Middle lane and the lane closest go to blue and the other lane goes to red, depending on what team you are. Bottom/Top Lane can effectively harass or kill the enemy with Red Buff as well as increasing their pushing and farming power slightly. Middle Lane gets a huge benefit of being able to spam spells with ease and allowing them to bully their enemy out of lane. Top Lane is going 2v1 so they don't need a buff to help since they already have the advantage, only being behind by usually 1-2 levels from then on once they both reach Level 3. When the buffs respawn, the closest lane can get Red and Middle Lane can get Blue again to gain back the advantage again AND deny them from the enemy jungler. The enemy jungler can go ahead and farm in the enemy jungle but they will find themselves gaining little benefits and using much more of their time farming than ganking when they could gain equal gold by simply farming from their own jungle by going between the constantly respawning monsters.

Good Top ADCs: {{champion:18}} {{champion:67}} {{champion:51}} {{champion:81}} {{champion:104}} {{champion:133}} {{champion:236}} {{champion:15}} {{champion:6}} {{champion:110}} 
Good Top Supports: {{champion:201}} {{champion:412}} {{champion:89}} {{champion:53}} {{champion:25}} 
Top Lane becomes home to the more aggressive supports that limit their opponents crowd control and/or mobility while having decent mobility themselves. The ADCs become the equally mobile and aggressive early game carries that can be found in current Bottom Lane such as Caitlyn, Ezreal, and Graves. Quinn and Urgot also have a home since they gain a support. Quinn becomes a much more aggressive ADC Fighter that can match the enemy Top Lane from a range and Urgot becomes a super harass champion that never really has to put himself in danger of a gank.

Good Middle Lanes: {{champion:34}} {{champion:103}} {{champion:69}} {{champion:38}} {{champion:7}} {{champion:127}} {{champion:99}} {{champion:61}} {{champion:134}} {{champion:45}} {{champion:115}} 
Suddenly these Mages become 100% more aggressive from the blue buff, enough to keep them safe to build items to continue their advantage. The blue buff advantage will also probably land them so sick kills. (Yes, Kassadin is really good again)

Good Bottom ADCs: {{champion:119}} {{champion:236}} {{champion:21}} {{champion:18}} {{champion:29}} {{champion:96}} {{champion:67}} 
Good Bottom Supports: {{champion:37}} {{champion:16}} {{champion:412}} {{champion:201}} {{champion:40}} {{champion:143}} {{champion:267}} {{champion:12}} {{champion:25}} 
Bottom Lane remains about the same, but will probably have much more late game ADCs in order to give your team the late game killing power it needs. The supports are much less about being aggressive and much more about keeping their carries safe from harm, although they can still initiate or control a fight when needed.

{{summoner:11}} can be picked up by the Top Lane or Bottom Lane support in order to still have that objective control of Dragon and Baron.

You don't need a jungler to take advantage of the buffs.
